# Data power positive deviance (for sustainable livestock farming)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Overview
Data Powered Positive Deviance (DPPD) is a method that combines traditional and non-traditional data sources to identify individuals or groups achieving better outcomes than their peers, despite similar resources and challenges.

## Purpose
The DPPD approach is used for Research and Development (R&D) in solving social issues by efficiently identifying outliers, reducing costs and time, providing context-aware insights, and enabling scalability of successful practices.

## How it works
The method involves five steps: assessing problem-method fit, determining positive deviants, discovering factors underlying outperformance, designing and implementing interventions, and monitoring and evaluating these interventions.

## Requirements
To effectively use DPPD for R&D, one needs proficiency in data analysis, access to reliable and diverse data sources, high-quality data, adequate technological infrastructure, financial resources, and human resources including data scientists, field researchers, and community facilitators.

## Reflections
When using DPPD, it is essential to consider data privacy and security, data quality and reliability, context sensitivity, community engagement, and ethical considerations related to data collection and consent.

## Related methods (if any)
Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning, data analysis, data collection, Data Ethography, and Data Visualisation

## License
Free or open

## Examples
The DPPD method has been used in various contexts, including a pilot project in Ecuador's Amazon to address deforestation and promote sustainable livestock farming practices.
